item.content:encoded: The Spring Season has Begun! Check out the practice info and schedule for more information. BWRFC is looking to add to our coaching staff. Boston Women's Rugby Football Club is an established rugby club fostering the spirit of rugby on and off the pitch for over 35 years. BWRFC welcomes individuals from all skill levels. We are a diverse team dedicated to achieving the highest standards of competitive rugby play. BWRFC has renewed itself as a national level contender with significant coaching changes and a recent influx of young talent. If you are interested in playing, email us or come by practice. Check us out on facebook and twitter! And please explore our website where we hope to give you a flavor of what we are about... Thanks for visiting.

item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded:
2012 Upcoming Events

February 7, 9, 14, & 18: 4th Annual BWRFC Bootcamp
BWRFC would like to extend an invitation to jump start your fitness for the spring season with us this February. We'll be dedicating two weeks of evening practices (dates and details below) to working on speed, conditioning, fitness, agility, and strength training. For our bootcamp sessions, we invite qualified trainers/teachers to create rugby-specific programs for us. These workouts are focused to help you better prepare your team (and yourself) for your spring season and can be incorporated into your fall training as well! Any interested player is welcome to come to 1, 2, 3 or all 4 sessions! Each session is just $5 (to pay for gym time) or attend all 4 for $15 and receive the 4th session free! It's a great opportunity to train to continue playing the sport you love beyond your college years. Meet players from other schools that you can schedule a friendly match with in the spring. Bring your teammates and reinvigorate your rugby-specific training, get workouts that you can use for your team beyond the spring season, and get ready to bring it on the pitch in 2012! E-mail us to sign up and get more info.
Week 1: Tuesday, February 7 (8:00-10:00pm) & Thursday, February 9 (7:00-9:00pm) Week 2: Tuesday, February 14 (8:00- 10:00pm) Thursday, February 16 (7:00-9:00pm)
Where: See our practice page for directions

EVENT CALENDAR

***Past Events***

2012: January 28: BWRFC and Old Gold Mens Rugby hosted the 3rd Annual New England Rugby Pub Crawl in the Fenway area. Thank you to the 200+ ruggers and friends who attended the crawl in their fanciest attire and tuxedo shirts. Big thanks to all of the bars that hosted us, especially Cask n' Flagon and Bleacher Bar for their generously donated gift certificates.

January 14: BWRFC supported the 2nd Annual FUSE: A Her HRC event at the Middle East Nightclub in Cambridge. It was an evening filled with music and entertainment for equality. 2011:

December 14: BWRFC players and alumni gathered at Cambridge Rehabilitation and Nursing Center to spread holiday warmth and cheer with seasonal carols.

December 3: BWRFC players gathered at Tommy Doyle's in Harvard Sq for the end of the season Holiday Party. Team awards were given out as well as a celebratory goodbye to our retiring players.

October 2: 16 current players and alumni volunteered for the Making Strides Against Breast Cancer Walk in Boston. We handed out snacks and water and cheered for a wonderful cause that has effected many of our teammates, family and friends. September 25: BWRFC scored a perfect 300 at Rookie Bowling Night tearing up the lanes with granny roll strikes, celebratory fist pumping displays and everything in between.Our vets spent quality time bonding with our awesome rookies who are a force to be reckoned with.

September 10: Our 35th Anniversary kicked off with an Alumni vs Current Players game at Moakley Park on a beautiful Saturday morning. Our Old Girls used their experience to come out ahead of well fought match. Then, the celebration continued into the night at the Green Briar with everyone from founding members to rookies celebrating the history of the first women's rugby club in Boston! Please see our photo gallery for pictures from the event.

August 21: BWRFC volunteered at the Giving Factory, part of Cradles to Crayons, assembling 57 outfit packs for soon to be stylish children in need. C2C provideschildren up to age 12 living in homeless and low-income situations with the essentials they need to be successful.

August 6: BWRFC went back in time to 1994 and flipp-flopped our way around Brighton on the Malibu Sands Beach Comber Bar Crawl.
July 19: End of the Summer 7's Season Party at the Banshee!
July 16: The 26th Annual Cape Cod 7's was a huge success! Please see the Cape Cod 7's page for more information. See the costumes in the photo gallery.
June 4: End of the Spring Season Party!
January 22: The 2nd Annual New England Pub Crawl took us around the Fenway area on Galactic Adventure.

2010: December 4: End of the season holiday party!

October 3: Making Strides for Breast Cancer walk!

May 22: BWRFC organized the Pub Scout Crawl! The scouts crawled along Mass Ave and stopped atMiddle East, Cantab, People's Republic, Tommy Doyle's, andfinished up at the Hong Kong!

May 18: BWRFC took over Fenway Park and watched the Red Soxs win!

Jan 20: Haiti Earthquake Relief Fundraiser.

 

2009:

Dec 21: BWRFC sang Christmas Carols at the Mt. Vernon Nursing Home in Cambridge. Dec 5: BWRFC along with Mystic River hosted the 1st Annual New England Rugby Pub Crawl.

Nov 21: BWRFC celebrated their End of the Season Party.

Oct 24-25: BWRFC, with Old Gold Rugby, hosted the WOMEN'S DI PLAYOFFS! BWRFC won Game 1 vs. Chicago North Shore 15-3, lost in Game 2 vs. NOVA 5-15

Oct 18: BWRFC and Old Gold RFC hosted a Level I Referee Course in conjuction with the New England Rugby Referee Society.

Oct 4: BWRFC volunteered at the Making Strides Against Breast Cancer Walk!

Aug 24th: Rookie Night!

Aug 11th: Cradles to Crayons

Aug 12th: BWRFC takes over Fenway!

June 28-29: Cape Cod Getaway MS Bike Ride

June 13: Relay for Life, Watertown

April 13: Jump into Spring - Strong Women, Strong Girls Boston! More events coming soon!

8/7/2011: Congratulations to BWRFC players Emily Malkin, Danielle Miano, and Stacy Powell for earning second place in USA Rugby's 7s Club Championship with the Boston Belles!

7/27/2011: BWRFC is proud of their players Emily Malkin and Danielle Miano for being selected to the NRU 7s roster. They will be preparing for the upcoming NASC Tournament at the Olympic Training Center in Chula Vista, CA on August 26th &27th.

4/4/2010: Boston.com article on women's rugby, BWRFC alumni interviewed 1/20/2010: Haiti Earthquake Relief Fundraiser The Haiti Earthquake Relief Fundraiser at the Banshee was one of our first successes for 2010 (with many more successful events to come)! Donations from those entering the bar were roughly $1,800, the bartenders were also kind enough to donate their tips, Ray and The Banshee contributed $1,000, and others who could not attend the event sent donations by mail resulting in a grand total of about $4,000!! This amount will go to the nonprofit HeartswithHaiti.org.

10/25-26/2008: BWRFC beats the Atlanta Harlequins 19-5 at Nationals!!! The Boston Women's Rugby Club would like to congratulate former BWRFC player Ashley Groefsema and the Berkeley All Blues for winning the USA Rugby Club Championship title for the second consecutive year! Ashley began her rugby career playing rugby at UCSB in the Fall of 2003. After graduating in 2004, Ashley traveled to the east coast and began playing with BWRFC in the fall of 2004. Ashley was an impact player on and off the field for BWRFC and you would most likely hear her voice directing everyone from the scrumhalf position. Sadly, Ashley moved back to the west coast to once again be with her family and play rugby with her sister, Blair, for the Berkeley All Blues. BWRFC certainly has had tough shoes to fill, however wishes Ashley all the best in her future. We miss you TRASH!

5/3/2008: BWRFC wins Colorado Challenge Match! 3/8/2008: BWRFC wins 2nd place at the Champagne Classic in San Diego! Erin Broderick was voted Tight 5 MVP of the tournament.

3/29/2008: BWRFC comes in 2nd at 4 Leafs Tournament!

item.title: Coaches, Captains, & Selectors
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded:
BWRFC Seeks New Coaching Staff

Team: The Boston Women's Rugby Club is a highly competitive DI Women's Rugby Club currently ranked #2 in the country. Throughout the Fall 2008 and Spring 2009 seasons, BWRFC played 10 of the top 16 teams in the country. The team is coming off a competitive and successful Fall and Spring season playing teams such as Berkley (#1), New York (#2), Beantown (#3), Keystone (#5) and victorious over the Atlanta Harlequinns (#8) at the USA Rugby DI Womens National Championships in St. Louis. With the Fall 2009 restructuring of the Womens D1 Structure, Boston Womens is recognized as the #2 DI team in the nation, and is looking to build off of the success of our previous seasons and continue to develop our team to new successes at the top of Division I Womens Club League.

Position: Coaches interested in joining BWRFC must: bring expertise to build on the foundation of our highly competitive team; have experience coaching (men's or women's teams, collegiate or club level); be available for T/Th evening practices, and weekend matches (both home and away); and be USA Rugby Certified or have obtained coaching experience at other clinics/courses/programs (Example: UQ Rugby Academy). The position includes a generous seasonal stipend.

Players: BWRFC currently has a roster of over 35+ women. The team is consistently fielding 2 strong sides at all games. Our players are a group of highly talented, motivated and competitive women seeking to play the best rugby in the Northeast. BWRFC has several players who are or have been members of both the U23 and Senior Women's Side Northeast Select Side Team. We also have a few USA rugby developmental players for 7's and 15's. We are a very young, athletic and talented group of players who are eager to become one of the top competitive teams in the country.

Interested applicants should contact the board.

COACHES

Coaches: Paul Harrop and Louis Rivers

CAPTAINS

Captain: Danielle Miano

Raised by Catholic Joseph Miano and Lutheran Robin Miano, Danielle Meow showed an affinity for sportsin as a pre-pubescent cub.The song Born in the USA was actually inspired by Danielles birth.At the ripe age of 18, Danielle journeyed to Western New Yorks inner thigh, SUNY Fredonia.Here she discovered the glory of the oval ball and galloped through her next four years as a multi-time MVP, captain, social chair, vice president, and general kitchen sink of the Fredonia Blackhorse DII Rugby Club, New York State Champs 2005.Once out of the barn, this kitten traveled east to pursue her dreams as a show poodle and technology industry professional.She joined BWRFC in the Fall of 2007.In her years with Boston Womens, shes served many roles including captain, social chair, and fullback. Danielle also travels the country, beating up ruggers 14 minutes at a time, playing for both the nationally ranked Boston Belles 7s Rugby team and the Northeast Rugby Union Regional 7s side.When not prancing around the pitch, Danielle enjoys general physical challenges such as break dancing, buffalo wing eating, rock climbing and slow pitch softball. Hidden talent: navigating the treacherous floors of the Hot Lava Game.Religious views: the only boss she listens to is Bruce Springsteen.Life dream: to one day compete for an Olympic Gold Medal in honor of the United States of America and to some day see the Buffalo Bills win a Superbowl.

item.title: New Players
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded:
Looking to play rugby?

Can't wait to put your boots back on? Interested in finding out more? Then drop us a lineand we'll answer all your questions. But to get you started, below is some information about BWRFC most new players want to know...

I've never played before/haven't played in a long time, can I still join?

Yes! BWRFC welcomes all players who are interested in playing competitive DI rugby. We field two teams to provide all players with the opportunity to play. Our coaches, captains, and veteran players are always around to help with the basics. If you're ready to work hard you will find yourself falling in love with rugby - for the first time or all over again.

When is practice?

That depends on the time of year, but during our Fall and Spring seasons we usually practice two nights a week and try to stick to Tuesday and Thursday evenings. Our practice times are flexible - check the practice schedule, or e-mail to get the most up-to-date information.

Where is practice?

Field space is often hard to find in Boston, so we are also flexible with our location, practicing wherever we can find a field with lights. We are often found at Moakley Field in South Boston, or English High School in Jamaica Plain, but we practice wherever we can find space - so e-mail for the most recent practice locations or check the practice schedule. We try to keep our practice locations T-accessible, but we also organize carpools - so please let us know if you need to find a way to practice.

What do I need for practice?

All you need for practice is general workout clothes (clothes you don't mind getting dirty), water, a mouthguard which you can pick up at any major sporting goods store, rugby shorts and cleats if you have them (molded cleats not metal studs for when we practice on turf) or sneakers, and a willingness to work hard and have a good time doing it. If you have never played before, don't worry about not having all the gear, pick up a moutguard and give practice a try.

More questions/concerns?

Send us a message via the form on the right,and we'll find an answer for you! Looking forward to meeting you on the pitch!

item.title: Venue
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded: DIRECTIONS: The tournament is located at the Nauset Regional High School in Eastham. The fields are located directly behind the high school and parking is available at the school. For driving directions, please use the following street address (or see below): Nauset Regional High School 100 Cable Road North Eastham, MA 02651 NOTE: Summer traffic from Boston and Providence to Cape Cod is extremely heavy (particularly if you are coming down Route I-93 on a Friday afternoon or Saturday morning). Please be sure to account for this in your travel plans. Once on the Cape (from Route 6): Travel past Exits 1-12 Follow Route 6 at the Rotary towards Eastham / Provincetown Proceed through HIGH TRAFFIC ENFORCEMENT AREA At the 4th light - about 4 miles (2 gas stations in front of you and Dunkin Donuts/Ben & Jerrys on your right) - take a RIGHT onto Brackett Road Follow Brackett Road to the end Take a LEFT onto Nauset Road, then a RIGHT onto Cable road (sign there for Nauset High School and Nauset Light) Go in the second entrance of Nauset Regional High School (left) Park in the lot on the RIGHT Fields are located behind the school. From Boston and points North (including Logan Airport): Take Route 93 South through Boston to Route 3 South (Exit 7) Take Route 3 South to Route 6 East toward Provincetown (cross the Sagamore Bridge) From here follow the Once on the Cape directions above. From Rhode Island and points South/West (including TF Green Airport): Take Route 95 North to Route 195 (Exit 20) Follow Route 195 East into Massachusetts to Route 25 East Route 25 East becomes Route 6 East Follow Route 6 East through the rotary and across the Sagamore Bridge From here follow the Once on the Cape directions above. item.title: Cape Cod Sevens Tournament
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded:
Get ready for the 27th Cape Cod Sevens Tournament on July 21st, 2012!

The theme is Battle of the Ages so in order to honor the world ending as the Mayans predicted, we encourage teams to dress as Vikings in 1200, Spartan Warriors, Crusades, Aztecs and more! Every year Boston Women's Rugby hosts one of the largest women's rugby sevens tournments in the country and this year it will be an NRU 7s Qualifier event! What distinguishes the Cape Cod Sevens from most of the other summer tournaments on the east coast is the mix of fierce competition (several of the country's 4 top-ranked women's teams every year) and chaotic fun (teams are strongly encouraged to play in costume!) Each year we carefully select a theme to which participating teams are "required" to conform - either in their on-field attire or in a skit performed at the post-tournament party. Past themes have included "Lost 45s," "The 70s," "Cartoon Capers", "Olympics", and "Movie Madness." Our tournament participants are as diverse as our themes. We have college teams, women's club teams, teams of "retired" players who have decided to dust off their boots, and a few teams united by some pretty odd commonalities: they all play the same position; they all have the same name; they all have the same color hair. The 2012 tournament will be held on Saturday, July 21st, in Eastham, MA and the theme is Battle of the Agesso be ready to dress as your favorite creepy character such asVikings, Crusades, Spartan Warriors,others. For those of you unfamiliar with the area, Cape Cod is a popular New England vacation spot; Eastham is located on Cape Cod about 2.5 hours southeast of Boston and a half hour from Provincetown (the tip of Cape Cod and the location of some excellent bars, shops and beaches). The tournament is a one-day event with competitive, social, college, and high school divisions. Teams of all levels are welcome to participate. Each team is guaranteed 3 matches. However, for teams who play through to the finals, the number can be far higher! Teams are encouraged to play in costume and our post-tournament social features a skit competition nearly as fierce as what we see on the pitch. Registration fees are: Number of Teams By June 15th By July 3rd 1 $200 $250 2 $350 $450 3 $500 $650 ***July 11this the LAST DAY to register! Please be sure to register before this date to ensure your team secures a spot in this year's tournament.*** Register online with credit card or PayPal! Or pay by check. Please make checks payable to Boston Womens Rugby Club. Please send the following information along with your check: Team Name Team Contact Person Address, Phone Number, E-mail Division Competitive, Social, Collegiate, or High School Please mail all registration information to: Maria Carolina Ruiz 12 Stoneholm Ave, Apt #413 Boston, MA 02155 If you would like more information about Cape Cod Sevens or have any questions, please do not hesitate tocontact us.

2011 Creepy Cape Cod 7s Social Information!

This year the social will be at a new location - Tommy Doyles in Hyannis! Besides the FREE food, beer, and live band, come to the social for the team and individual awards ceremony, the raffle, and skit competition. Also make sure to dress to impress as the person with the best Halloween costume will get a special prize! There will be a buffet that starts at 7:00pm and it will be a first come, first serve deal. The first 100 beers are free so make sure you arrive early! Thereafter, Narragansett and PBR cans will only be $3. Music will be playing throughout the night provided by the skit competition starting at 8:00pm, a DJ at 9:00pm, and then a live band at 10:00pm. We will have our own private room that has an outdoor patio until 9:30pm and then the room will be open to the public. But no need to fear as there is plenty of room to get your groove on. Tommy Doyles is open until 1am and there are many hotels within walking distance (see CC7s Accomodation page). Where: Tommy Doyle's 334 Main St, Hyannis, MA 02673 When: 7:00PM your dancing shoes fall off Directions from the Field:

item.title: Rugby Skill Development
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded:
Types of Kicks In Rugby

(click on kick types for videos) Spiral punt kick (torpedo) Bomb (Up and Under) kick Grubber kick Chip kick, Chip kick 2 Cross kick Banana kick

Rugby Skill Rubrics

Catch / Pass
  • Outside foot up to stay square and straight
  • Hands out towards pass
  • Fingers up
  • Elbows bent to absorb impact (soft elbows)
  • Catch ball early
  • Bring across body at above hip height across the table in fluid motion
  • Keep hips and shoulders square
  • Turn head towards receiver
  • Release firm pass with wrist flick
  • Fingers finish pointed toward receiver

Click here for video courtesy of the University of Queensland Rugby Academy

Pass Extension Drill #1
  • Performed on knees
  • Ball tucked under one hip on side
  • Power / force / spin hand wrapped around ball at the back of the ball
  • Other hand guiding ball
  • Pass ball straight out in front to partner
  • Use torso to generate more power in pass

Click here for video courtesy of the NSW T7s

Pass Extension Drill #2
  • Same as above, on knees, except one-handed
  • Pass goes across body from one side to the other
  • Power hand only grips ball on hip
  • Power hand only rips pass across the table with spin motion
  • Repeat with partner
Tackle
  • Tackler aims for inside shoulder of ball carrier
  • Maintain balance
  • Weight forward on feet to change direction
  • Defender takes the space and get in tight
  • Pick a target area
  • Hit, stick, squeeze and leg drive after contact
  • Regain feet to play the ball

Click here for video courtesy of the Ford Rugby Academy

item.title: Team
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded: Boston Women's Rugby is a Division 1 club rugby team, part of the Northeast Rugby Union (NRU). We welcome players new and experienced who want to play top tier, high-caliber rugby.

item.title: Club
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded: Boston Women's Rugby Football Club was found in 1976, and is the oldest women's rugby team on the east coast. We have a strong tradition of active alumni involvement, as well as volunteerism within our local community.

item.title: Alumni
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded: BWRFC is the oldest women's rugby team in Boston, and credit is due to our active and supportive alumni. Celebrating 35 years in 2011, we welcome all Boston girls to our games and events.

item.title: BWRFC beats the Atlanta Harlequins 19-5
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded: Boston Women's Rugby Club would like to congratulate former BWRFC player Ashley Groefsema and the Berkeley All Blues for winning the USA Rugby Club Championship title for the second consecutive year! Ashley began her rugby career playing rugby at UCSB in the Fall of 2003. After graduating in 2004, Ashley traveled to the east coast and began playing with BWRFC in the fall of 2004. Ashley was an impact player on and off the field for BWRFC and you would most likely hear her voice directing everyone from the scrumhalf position. Sadly, Ashley moved back to the west coast to once again be with her family and play rugby with her sister, Blair, for the Berkeley All Blues. BWRFC certainly has had tough shoes to fill, however wishes Ashley all the best in her future. We miss you TRASH!

item.title: Haiti Earthquake Relief Fundraiser
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded: The Haiti Earthquake ReliefFundraiserat theBansheewas one of our first successes for 2010 (with many more successful events to come)! Donations from those entering the bar were roughly $1,800, the bartenders were also kind enough to donate their tips. Ray and The Banshee contributed $1,000, and others who could not attend the event sent donations by mail resulting in a grand total of about $4,000!! This amount will go to the nonprofitHeartswithHaiti.org.

item.title: Cradles to Crayons Volunteer Event
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded: BWRFC volunteered at the Giving Factory, part of Cradles to Crayons, assembling 57 outfit packs for soon to be stylish children in need. C2C provideschildren up to age 12 living in homeless and low-income situations with the essentials they need to be successful.

item.title: BWRFC Celebrates Its 35th Anniversary!
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded: Our 35th Anniversary kicked off with an Alumni vs Current Players game at Moakley Park on a beautiful Saturday morning. Our Old Girls used their experience to come out ahead of well fought match. Then, the celebration continued into the night at the Green Briar with everyone from founding members to rookies celebrating the history of the first women's rugby club in Boston! Please see ourphoto galleryfor pictures from the event.

item.title: Rookie Bowling Night!
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded: BWRFC scored a perfect 300 at Rookie Bowling Night tearing up the lanes with granny roll strikes, celebratory fist pumping displays and everything in between.Our vets spent quality time bonding with our awesome rookies who are a force to be reckoned with.

item.title: 4th Annual BWRFC Bootcamp
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded:
BWRFC would like to extend an invitation to jump start your fitness for the spring season with us this February. We'll be dedicating two weeks of evening practices to working on speed, conditioning, fitness, agility, and strength training.
For our bootcamp sessions, we invite qualified trainers/teachers to create rugby-specific programs for us. These workouts are focused to help you better prepare your team (and yourself) for your spring season and can be incorporated into your fall training as well!
Any interested player is welcome to come to 1, 2, 3 or all 4 sessions! Each session is just $5 (to pay for gym time) or attend all 4 for $15 and receive the 4th session free! It's a great opportunity to train to continue playing the sport you love beyond your college years. Meet players from other schools that you can schedule a friendly match with in the spring.
Bring your teammates and reinvigorate your rugby-specific training, get workouts that you can use for your team beyond the spring season, and get ready to bring it on the pitch in 2012! E-mail us to sign up and get more info.
Week 1: Tuesday, February 7 (8:00-10:00pm) & Thursday, February 9 (7:00-9:00pm)
Week 2: Tuesday, February 14 (8:00- 10:00pm) Thursday, February 16 (7:00-9:00pm)
